post_text: Way to go Jays and Lady Jays!
shared_text:
PORTA High School Bluejay Cross Country
August 29 at 11:40 AM ·

We opened the Sangamo Conference this morning with a Boy/Girl Double meet win! Girls win over Maroa-Forsyth and North Mac 22 to 45 to 64. In the boys standings PORTA/AC won 20 to 47 over Maroa-Forsyth. North Mac did not have a boys team.
Top 5 Lady Jay scores were Senior Jenna Kesselring who got the meet win at 20:28, in 3rd overall was Hannah Schafer at 21:33, 4th overall was Emma Baker at 22:39, 5th overall was Lauren Harrison at 22:57, and 9th overall was Arabella Dikmans at 25:55. Top 5 Boy Bluejay Scores we’re Freshmen (yes he’s only a freshmen!) Haven Gronewold in 2nd at 16:46, Cameron McCoy at 18:08, Aden Mathis at 18:49, Senior Clayton Miller at 19:24 and Daxton Trueblood at 19:31. Outstanding first meet! Let’s do it all again next week at Mason City vs. the Illini Central Cougars and Williamsville Bullets! Go PXC! Go Bluejays!!!

Beginning Band Night will be on Thursday, September 3rd from 4:30 - 6:30pm in front of A-C Central Middle School. This is a change from the original date, time, and location.

5th graders and anyone starting band for the first time will have the opportunity to try out instruments and ask questions.

We will be using at least two sets of mouthpieces for the trial instruments and sanitizing between uses. As such, Beginning Band Night will operate in 10-minute time slots with two families per shift.

Please type in your name in the earliest time slot for which you are available using this link: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1ZFM-9sBavzuyOOSq1HR7OroufsbrNKapbuQsshcGckU/edit?usp=sharing

If you cannot make it but are interested in band or have any questions, please contact me at awilson@a-ccentral.us.

Thank you, and I hope to see you soon!

Mr. Wilson
Band Director
A-C Central CUSD #262

A band parent meeting will be held on Tuesday, August 18th at 6pm in the MS/HS cafeteria to discuss how band will look similar and different due to COVID-19. This meeting will cover plans for 5th through 12th grade band students. As things can change often and quickly in a pandemic, questions will be answered with the most current information available.

If you have questions or concerns but cannot attend or do not feel comfortable attending, please email Mr. Wilson at awilson@a-ccentral.us.

Please enter through the northwest doors and provide at least six feet of space between families. Due to safety regulations, you will need a face covering and may be temperature and symptom screened. If possible, please bring a Clorox or sanitizing wipe to clean your chair and table after the meeting.

--
Austin Wilson
Band Director
A-C Central CUSD #262
Thank you!

post_text: The A-C Central JH softball and baseball teams will have their first games tomorrow, 8/15. We are excited for our student-athletes to have the opportunity to play. However, with this opportunity comes certain guidelines that have to be followed. For games at Nate's Park attendance will be limited to 50 people per school. The players and coaches do count towards the 50 people limit. To keep our count below 50, each player can only bring 2 family members to the game with them. We ask that if you are not one of the two family members of a player that you do not attend the game. While at the game, please practice the 6 feet rule of social distancing. If you are unable to social distance please wear a mask. Please do your part in helping with this opportunity for our student-athletes to continue to play in athletic contests.

Good morning. This is Mrs. Shaver calling from the unit office with two important announcements.

First, IESA has decided to have a fall season after all. Starting Tuesday, 8/4 the baseball team will practice from 9:00-11:00am daily. The bus will leave from Ashland at 8:30.
The softball team will practice from 4:30-6:00pm daily. The bus will leave Ashland at 4:00.

Second, this is a reminder that registration packet drop off is this week at both the middle and high school in Ashland and elementary school in Chandlerville. Packets may be dropped off at either location in the plastic tote outside the main doors in Ashland and the East office doors at Chandlerville from 8-3 daily and 12-7 on Wednesday. Should additional forms be required for your student to register and copies are needed, please ring the intercom bell and secretaries will assist you.

Parents - please drop off registration packets no later than Friday 8/7 so that an accurate count of students can be determined.

Registration packets for the 2020/21 school year were mailed today, July 27.

Completed packets may be returned by mail or dropped off at either school from Monday, August 3 - Friday, August 7 from 8am to 3pm. On Wednesday, August 5th hours will be extended from 12pm-7pm. No in person registration will be conducted this year.

Plastic containers for packet drop off will be located outside of each school building, at the front entrance at the MS/HS and at the East office entrance at the Elementary School in Chandlerville.

Middle and High School students needing to change their schedule should email Mrs. Hoesman at rhoesman@a-ccentral.us.

Any questions regarding transportation should be directed to the Transportation Secretary by texting or calling 312-884-1398, emailing rgilpin@a-ccentral.us, or by calling the unit office at (217) 476-8112 extension 1110.

post_text:
Good afternoon. This is Mrs. Shaver calling with several important announcements:

1st - The last of summer school report cards were mailed out today 7/24/2020. If you have any questions or concerns regarding any summer school grades, feel free to contact the MS/HS office.

2nd - After much discussion, the IESA Board unanimously approved to cancel the regular season and IESA state series in the sports of boys and girls golf, boys baseball, girls softball, and boys and girls cross-country for the 2020-21 school year. There are no plans to try and re-schedule the activities or conduct them later in the school year.

3rd - Tonight is our 8th grade virtual graduation ceremony. Please join us in celebrating our 8th grade graduates tonight at 7pm by accessing the virtual graduation link via facebook or via our website. Congratulations to all of our 8th grade graduates.

post_text:
5th graders completed a unit on the Revolutionary War during the school closure. Part of the unit was learning about the causes that lead to the war. They were given the task of creating a protest poster fitting for that time period based on what they learned about the causes. They were to submit it as a picture of them holding the poster in protest for some extra fun.
Happy Independence Day!
text:
5th graders completed a unit on the Revolutionary War during the school closure. Part of the unit was learning about the causes that lead to the war. They were given the task of creating a protest poster fitting for that time period based on what they learned about the causes. They were to submit it as a picture of them holding the poster in protest for some extra fun.
Happy Independence Day!

post_text:
Interested in joining the Bluejays Dance Team!?

The Dancing Jays is writing to YOU to invite you to tryouts! Practices are June 22nd-June 24th from 9:30-11:00am. Our team has so much fun, but we also love to focus on bettering ourselves as dancers and students. We dance at football and basketball games, but you do have the choice of just doing 1 season if you’re involved in other sports throughout the year. Don’t be worried if you don’t have any dance experience, we have a few days of practices before tryouts so you can learn the basics, and we also go to camp in the summer to improve all of our skills before the season starts! We have a reasonable practice schedule and dancing is a great stress reliever! If you have a friend that might be interested please invite them to tryout with you!! Please contact Coach Puckett or any member of the team if you have any questions - hope to see you next week!

Lora Puckett

Coach

217-414-3385

lpuckett@porta202.org

Mrs. Davis's 5th grade Science classes participated in a Mock Science Fair during A-C's remote learning days. Students were given written instruction along with a diagram to follow to set up their boards. Twenty-two 5th graders participated and thirteen students placed in the Mock Science Fair!

In 5-A class, the first place winners are Hailey H., Josh M., Trey R., and Grady S. 5-B first place winners are Chelan C. and Austin H.

Second place winners are Chase J. in 5-A and in 5-B are Ethan H., Jaycee G., Anthony L., and Macy S.

Third place winners are Kayden J. in 5-A and Charlee R. in 5-B. A big shout out goes to all of the participating students for their accomplishments during our first ever (and hopefully our last) Pandemic Remote learning period. CONGRATULATIONS KIDS!

Many of the students submitted photos of their completed Science Fair projects. Great job 5th Grade!

post_text:
Good Evening. This is Mrs. Shaver calling with an important announcement for all Middle and High School students and parents.

Tomorrow, Monday June 1 will be our final pick up and drop off date. Check out for grades 5-8 is from 9 am to noon, and check out for grades 9-11 is from 1-3 pm.

All students and parents should enter through the East entrance at Circle Drive. We ask that parents and students wear masks or other appropriate facial coverings at this time.

Also, if your student did not or was unable to complete all work during the remote learning period, administration will be contacting you beginning this week regarding summer learning opportunities.

We would like to thank our parents for being our partners in the education of our students during this unique educational experience and wish you a safe and relaxing summer. Thank you, and we’ll see many of you tomorrow!

Today State FFA announced the state proficiency winners during a Facebook live event. Usually this would take place at State Awards Day, but with COVID-19, it was done online.

post_text:
Congratulations to Jayce Privia for being named an IESA Scholar Attitude Award Winner!!
Jayce has participated in softball, basketball, and volleyball all 4 years of her Jr. High career.
A panel of judges consisting of coaches, athletic directors, principals, and superintendents reviewed the applications and selected one student from each of the 15 IESA membership divisions for the award. To be considered, a student from an IESA member school must be of 8th grade status, have a minimum grade-point-average of 3.5 on a 4.0 scale, must have participated in at least one IESA activity during each year of their two-year junior high career, and demonstrated outstanding citizenship during their junior high tenure. In addition, each student is required to submit an essay titled "The Value of Sportsmanship." You can see all 15 division winners at https://www.iesa.org/sportsmanship/sca/index.asp?Year=2020
*This is the 2nd year in a row that A-C Central has had an athlete win the IESA Scholar Attitude Award. Last year's winner was current freshman, Landon Smith.
#ACProud

post_text:
Dear A-C Central Families:

I hope this message finds you and your families safe and well. Today, Illinois Gov. JB Pritzker announced that remote learning in Illinois will be extended through April 30 in order to slow down the spread of COVID-19.

During this time, on-site learning will remain suspended but our schools’ commitment to learning and education will remain open and learning will continue for all students - just through a different format. While it is not ideal, we want to assure you that at A-C Central, our teachers and staff are fully engaged and willing to take on this new challenge and push forward with remote learning, engaging with students and continuing with our food distribution program every weekday with the exception of Good Friday, and Easter Monday.

I know this is not the school year that any of us imagined, but I want to thank you for your patience and understanding as we have dealt with this unprecedented situation together.

Please stay safe!

post_text: This year, the A-C Central BETA club wanted to extend their service hours to our own students. After finding out that there is a need for one on one reading time with students, eight BETA club members signed up to spend 20 min each day with middle school students. Mentors use different strategies with the students to improve upon their reading fluency or reading comprehension skills. After just two months, their teachers are noticing some drastic improvement. Another bonus has been the relationships developed between middle schoolers and high schoolers. When asked, the middle school students said that they really enjoy the one on one time and can tell that they are improving! Thanks to Beta members Alexis Reid, Payton Marr, Ainsley Mahoney, Skylar Arthalony, Claire Greer, Sydney Wallbaum, Bailey Wallbaum, and Gabe Carlock for making a difference!

post_text: The A-C Central High School Beta Club traded in their first 550 lbs of plastic in return for a picnic table in honor of Rachel Savage Wilkerson. Rachel’s Recycling is the new name for the Beta recycling program as Rachel was our biggest supporter during our first year. The table will be placed in the senior lunch courtyard for each class to enjoy when they are seniors. Rachel is missed each day and this is just a small way to honor her. Thanks to Mr. Mason Vincent, Greg Lange and Kim Webster for taking a day of their time over Spring Break to haul and trade the plastic in at Greentree Plastics in Evansville, IN.

post_text: Officer Larry Cave was asked to visit the 6th grade Character Education class. Students are learning about how making quick behavior decisions based an escalated emotional feeling can lead to life long consequences. Officer Cave shared his experiences as an officer and prison guard. He recounted how an inmates life is completely controlled by the prison, their freedom is taken away. Many of them talk about how they ended up there out of anger or thoughtless actions that cost them dearly. Cave also talked about the negative consequences that can result from improper behavior on social media sites, and the digital footprint that is left for anyone to look up even years from now. Thank you Officer Cave!

Other drivers reported that winds had picked up and visibility was becoming an issue. I am very sorry for the late change

post_text:
A brief update regarding the incident at A-C Central MS-HS yesterday:

Illinois State Police informed me today that the suspect remains in custody and charges have been filed. During their investigation that followed, they did recover a firearm and it is possible that he had it with him while he was on campus.

Please know that our student’s safety and well-being is our prime concern, and we continue to take every precaution we can to ensure the safety of all students and staff. I want to say again that I am extremely proud of all students and staff for their response to this crisis.

Thank you.

Sincerely,

Timothy M. Page
Superintendent of Schools
A-C Central CUSD #262

Our 8th Grade Student of the Month for December is Ethan Mahoney.
Ethan is known for his positive and pleasant attitude with everyone he interacts with. He is responsible and strives for success both academically and in extra-curricular activities. His honesty is valued by A-C Central staff, as is his willingness to help others and collaborate effectively with his peers. Ethan is a positive role model in school as a member of Student Council, as well as on the baseball field and basketball court. He also represented A-C Central at the regional science fair last year, where he earned a silver ranking. We are proud to call Ethan Mahoney an A-C Central Knight!

A-C Central is pleased to announce that Kyia Privia was chosen from the graduating class of 2019 as an Illinois State Scholar.

The Illinois Student Assistance Commission (ISAC), the state agency committed to helping to make college accessible and affordable for Illinois families, confers this prestigious recognition to top Illinois high school students annually. This year, more than 21,000 honorees join the other top students who have been honored for their academic achievements since the designation was first introduced in 1958.

Illinois State Scholars represent approximately the top ten percent of high school seniors from 757 high schools across the state. Illinois State Scholars are chosen based on a combination of exemplary ACT or SAT test scores and sixth semester class rank.

Congratulations Kyia!!

post_text: The A-C Central High School Beta Club and Middle School Student Council joined together to hold a food drive for the Cass County Food Bank which had recently run out of food. The Beta Club went on a scavenger hunt for certain food items and held a pack the place night which fans were requested to bring a food donation when entering the game. The Middle School Student Council requested cash or food donations for entry to the Middle School Halloween Dance. The Beta Club delivered and sorted all of the food on Nov 14th. The combined donation was $145 cash and 560 food/pantry items!

post_text: 5th graders have been learning about pumpkins and doing some hands on activities in Mrs. Davis' class. These pictures show them cleaning out a pumpkin and counting the amount of seeds in each. This activity was tied to their Math lessons. Over two class periods we learned how pumpkins grow and how many pumpkins can be yielded from one small seed. They did a prepared activity where pumpkins were grown for a school fundraiser. Kids had to figure out how many plants they could grow in a specific area, and then calculate the the number of pumpkins they would harvest. Lastly, they found out the amount of money that would be earned by the sale of the pumpkins. Each student took home a bag of pumpkin seeds.

post_text: Once again at the Veterans' Day assembly, fifth graders collected donations to sponsor wreaths for placement on a veteran's grave at Camp Butler National Cemetery during the Christmas season. Donations collected this year enabled A-C Central to sponsor 15 wreaths so far. Donations will be accepted in the office until Friday November 15, 2019. Thanks goes out to everyone who has already donated or plan to donate. The fifth graders learned about a fantastic way to remember our veterans!
